@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(v) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it builds a LIST (`[1, 2, 3]`) and sums it — a heap value the
-- compute spine has no representation for yet. The differential harness must report
-- it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal at the compiler frontier — never a miscompile,
-- never a JS crash.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records — built, field-read, and `PRecord`-destructured
-- (see compile_record_test). The frontier now sits at the remaining heap values —
-- LISTS and closures-as-values. This file builds a list, so it still refuses; when
-- lists lower (a later D1 slice), it flips from `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

def count(xs: List(Number)): Number
  length(xs)

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  println(count([1, 2, 3]))
